# Vercel + Turbo Build Rules

## Goal

Keep CI/Vercel builds deterministic for this Turborepo + Next.js monorepo.

## Node / package manager

- Respect the repo-level `package.json#engines.node`. If Vercel Project Settings specify a different major, the repo `engines` wins.
- Use the repo `package.json#packageManager` (pnpm) for all install/build commands.

## Turbo + environment variables

- If a build relies on environment variables in Vercel, ensure they are declared in `turbo.json` (so tasks receive them on Vercel).
- Prefer scoping env vars to the smallest set of tasks/packages that need them (e.g. `packages/@tinadmin/telnyx-ai-platform#build`).

## Type safety during Next builds

- Next.js builds run TypeScript checks; avoid `string | null` leaking into required `string` fields.
- When a value is guarded by runtime checks, make the type-narrowing explicit (e.g. non-null assertion after a `!value` early return) and add a final safe fallback for UI strings.

## Dependency build scripts (Vercel)

- Vercel may ignore dependency build scripts by default (e.g. `sharp`, `esbuild`); don’t assume postinstall scripts run in CI.
- If native deps are required at build time, prefer prebuilt binaries and avoid relying on postinstall compilation.

